<li>Based on these results , we propose that Mlc functions to sense the availability of sugars and is linked to virulence gene regulation by its ability to control hilE expression in Salmonella .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17329372" target="_blank">17329372</a>]<br></li>
<li>Salmonella may use Mlc to sense the availability of sugars , thereby allowing decisions as to when and where to initiate the expression of genes involved in invasion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17329372" target="_blank">17329372</a>]<br></li>
<li>speG modulates SPI-1 virulence because phosphotransferase controls the global transcription regulator Mlc for the complete expression of hilA , hilD , and invF ( Poncet et al. , 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29187844" target="_blank">29187844</a>]<br></li>
<li>The hilE gene , which encodes a negative regulator of SPI-1 gene-expression , possesses three promoters , one of which is controlled by the Mlc repressor ( Lim et al. , 2007 ) , which responds to the availability of glucose , and another that is controlled by the FimZ activator ( Baxter and Jones , 2005 ) , which also regulates Salmonella attachment and adherence under static growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21570144" target="_blank">21570144</a>]<br></li>
